II. PRELIMINARY
A. Problem Scope and Definition
Multimodal tactile fusion [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9] studies how tactile information is integrated with other modalities to support perception, generation, and interaction in robotic systems. In this survey, we focus on settings in which tactile sensing plays a central role and is combined with vision and/or language. Specifically, we consider the bimodal settings
T-V and T-L, as well as the trimodal setting T-V-L. Recent studies [2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7] have increasingly adopted the T-V-L setting because it provides a unified framework for connecting physical interaction, visual context, and semantic reasoning. From a modeling perspective, multimodal tactile fusion can be viewed as a multi-stage pipeline that maps physical interaction signals to computational representations. Unlike vision or language, tactile signals are inherently contact-driven and arise only through physical interaction. Accordingly, the multimodal tactile fusion process can be described by the following hierarchical stages.
1) Physical Transduction and Spatiotemporal Observation: During interaction, tactile sensors convert physical stimuli such as deformation, force, or vibration into digital signals. The raw inputs can be written as
xt ∈ RSt×Tt×Ct , xv ∈ RSv×Tv×Cv , xl ∈ V L, (1)
where xt denotes tactile observations with spatial configuration St, temporal length Tt, and channel dimension Ct, while xv and xl denote visual and language inputs, respectively.
2) Modality-Specific Representation Learning: Because different modalities have heterogeneous input formats, each modality is encoded into a latent representation:
zm = Em(xm; θm), m ∈ {t, v, l}, (2)
where Em(·) denotes a modality-specific encoder. This step transforms tactile, visual, and language inputs into learned representations, yielding zt, zv, zl ∈ Rd when all three modalities are available.
3) Cross-Modal Fusion and Joint Representation: The resulting unimodal representations are then integrated into a shared joint representation for downstream learning:
zjoint = Φ({zm}m∈M; θΦ), (3)
where M ⊆ {t, v, l} denotes the set of available modalities, and Φ(·) denotes the fusion operator. Depending on the


