reliance on paired task-specific supervision. Overall, this area has progressed from isolated supervised translation pipelines to more unified representation frameworks. Recent approaches increasingly treat high-quality vision-tactile generation not only as a standalone task, but also as a natural outcome of robust and scalable multimodal alignment.
2) Language-Tactile Generation and Translation:
a) Tactile-to-Language Description Generation: Tactileto-language generation translates tactile signals into natural language descriptions, such as texture, compliance, and local geometry, helping bridge the gap between raw physical contact and semantic reasoning. Unlike visual captioning, this task focuses on contact-centered semantics, making tactile perception more interpretable for human-robot communication and high-level decision-making.
Foundational Cross-Modal Alignment: Early frameworks approached tactile description generation mainly through joint representation learning. For example, Tactile-VLM [3] maps sensory inputs into a unified vision-language space, while UniTouch [2] leverages pretrained vision-language models to support zero-shot description generation without task-specific supervision. These studies show that robust cross-modal alignment is a key prerequisite for tactile-to-language generation. Grounded and Interactive Generation: More recent methods move toward more explicitly grounded and open-ended language generation. CLTP [5] decodes fine-grained contact states, such as shape and depth, directly from tactile arrays, whereas VTV-LLM [8] extends this capability to temporal vision-tactile streams for dynamic interactions. To improve semantic richness, recent architectures increasingly incorporate retrieval-augmented mechanisms. RA-Touch [13] uses external vision-language knowledge to refine descriptions, and Octopi1.5 [83] adopts lightweight retrieval for real-time and contextaware responses in interactive settings. In addition, SToLa [51] moves beyond rigid template-based captions toward free-form descriptions and tactile commonsense reasoning. Overall, this line of work shows a clear transition from basic representation alignment to more interactive and retrievalaugmented generation, where language increasingly serves as a general interface for multimodal tactile understanding.
